gs":[{"name":"Walford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from one or more of several places so named, such as Walford (Herefordshire), Walford in Leintwardine (also Herefordshire), Walford in Baschurch (Shropshire), and possibly Walford Hall in Hampton in Arden (Warwickshire), though this last may be a manorial placename deriving from the surname. The Herefordshire placenames probably derive from Old English <i>walh</i> ‘foreigner, Welshman’ (genitive plural <i>wala</i>) + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. The Shropshire placename derives from Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’ + <i>ford</i>. If it does not derive from the surname, the Warwickshire placename probably has the same etymology as the Herefordshire placenames.","perhaps occasionally a habitational name from Walford in Wimborne Minster (Dorset). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>walt</i> ‘unsteady’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Walford was born in 1441, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Robert Walford. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"1441–":"1441–Surnud","1432–1471":"1432–1471","144